==English==

===Etymology===
From the cross (Latin ''crux'') worn by Crusaders.

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
'''Crusade'''<!-- really always capitalised? -->

# One of a series of ostensibly [[religious]] [[campaign]]s by [[Christian]] forces from the 11th to the 13th century, mostly to capture the [[Holy Land]] from the [[Muslim]]s who occupied it.
# A grand concerted effort toward some purportedly worthy cause.

====Usage Note====
Use of the word ''crusade'' for a [[campaign]] on behalf of a noble cause is inadvisable for international use. The original Crusades were wars waged by [[Christian]]s on [[Muslims]]. A "crusade" against, say, the deadly disease [[smallpox]] would sound inappropriate and sinister in many parts of the world. The Arabic word [[jihad]] has much the same connotation in reverse; it may be used for totally worthy causes, and also for religious wars.

